diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can affect multiple systems in the body, causing a wide range of symptoms including psychosis, leukopenia, pleural effusion, acute pericarditis, and nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily affecting the joints, severe rheumatoid arthritis can also involve other tissues, potentially causing pleural effusion, pericarditis, and rare instances of nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease combines features of multiple autoimmune diseases including systemic lupus erythematosus, and can present with pleural effusion, pericarditis, and nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.rationale: Certain medications can induce lupus-like symptoms including pleural effusion, pericarditis, and leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis can cause granulomas in various tissues, potentially leading to pleural effusion, acute nephritis, and rare cases of heart and neurological involvement resulting in psychosis and pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.rationale: Certain types of lymphoma can present with leukopenia due to bone marrow infiltration, pleural effusion from lymphatic involvement, and rarely, pericarditis and nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.rationale: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it can lead to symptoms like leukopenia and, though rare, complications such as pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Viral Hepatitis
diagnoses.rationale: Certain types, like hepatitis B and C, can have extrahepatic manifestations including nephritis and, rarely, complications that resemble autoimmune diseases.

diagnoses.name: Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Bacterial infection of the heart valves can lead to a wide variety of symptoms depending on the severity and spread of infection, including rare cases of nephritis and pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.rationale: TB can cause pleural effusion and, more rarely, pericarditis. It can indirectly lead to leukopenia by affecting bone marrow function or through the side effects of medications used in treatment.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke is a medical emergency, and prompt treatment is crucial.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraine with aura is a type of migraine that involves neurological disturbances such as visual, sensory, or motor symptoms that precede the headache phase of the migraine attacks.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage. Often called a ministroke, a TIA may be a warning.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Brain tumors can begin in your brain (primary brain tumors), or cancer can begin in other parts of your body and spread to your brain (secondary, or metastatic, brain tumors).

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers and causes communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Cerebral Aneurysm
diagnoses.description: A cerebral aneurysm refers to a weak spot on a brain artery that balloons or bulges out and fills with blood. It can press on a nerve or surrounding tissue, and if it bursts or ruptures, it can lead to a hemorrhagic stroke.

diagnoses.name: Posterior Reversible Encephalopathy Syndrome (PRES)
diagnoses.description: Posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome (PRES) is a disorder characterized by a headache, confusion, seizures, and visual loss that can be reversible if recognized promptly and treated correctly.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the fluid and membranes surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Encephalitis is inflammation of the brain. There are several causes, but the most common is viral infection. Encephalitis often causes only mild flu-like signs and symptoms — such as a fever or headache — or no symptoms at all.
